                "name": "Miguel Bernabeu",
                "href": "/profile/Miguel-Bernabeu"
            },
            "answer_text": "To answer your question we would need to first define what is 'science' and what is the entire discipline. Science nowadays does not completely adhere to the original philosophy, but if we restrict ourselves to that origin we may be able to define science. Originally, science was the application of the scientific method which was simply a rational and methodic approach to discover anything, coming from empirism and positivism. A simplification of the method would be: 1- Assume you don't know anything about how something works2- Try to interact with it in a repeatable way and measure the response (experiment)3- Repeat the interactions and see if results are repeatable. (consistency and repeatability)4- Propose an explanation of the responses with respect to the interactions you did (hypothesis)5- Try to look for corner cases of your explanation6- Predict the outcomes using your explanation7- Reproduce the conditions of a corner case and measure the response. (if it doesn't fit, the hypothesis doesn't hold, so back to #4) If your prediction was correct, your hypothesis holds. Now you should share your data and hypothesis with other scientists so they do the same experiments and validate your results, try to find other cases and check your hypothesis' validity. If they do, then it appears to be true, it's a Theory. Scientists will check your methods, your data, your experiments, your conclusions, reproduce and alter the settings, look for variations, check internal consistency of the hypothesis, try to disprove your hypothesis and look for contradictions with other hypothesis and Theories. So, do scientists question Science? They should from within Science.  Do they question it from outside the framework? Well, they did. It really is part of philosophy so it was criticised and reviewed for a long time and was improved. Since then, minor adjustments were made to include other branches of science and transform into a generalist definition of the method instead of an empirical one. Finally, questioning the Discipline from outside would be to question the philosophy behind it, which would be a philosopher's job, not a scientist's. ",
