                "name": "Adriana Heguy",
                "href": "/profile/Adriana-Heguy"
            },
            "answer_text": "Every scientist should have had some training in the philosophy of science, and also epistemology, which is basically the theory of knowledge (http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epistemology). Honestly I think in some countries, for example in the US, it's not a requirement to become a scientist but it should be. At the very minimum, scientists should of course have thought long and hard about what constitutes valid knowledge, and how it is acquired and revised.  All scientists agree that using the scientific method (with modifications according to the specific field) is the most reliable way that we have of learning about the natural world, and all scientists agree that the truths science deals with are provisional as new data may bring on revisions to the current state of knowledge. If a scientist were to think that the scientific method is flawed to the point of being useless, then it would be hard for that person to continue working as a scientist, because she /he works run into problems getting data that other scientists would consider reliable. But it's not like we sign some sort of pact that we cannot question certain things or we have to return our PhDs. Is actually very interesting that distinguishing science from non-science, in other words the demarcation problem, is very easy at the extremes but there are disciplines and fields that do get questioned because they do not use or cannot use the \"classic\" version of the scientific method. Philosopher of science and evolutionary biologist Massimo Pigliucci wrote a very nice book on this subject called Nonsense on Stilts : how to tell science from bunk (http://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/N/bo5812109.html). I highly recommend it to scientists and lay people alike. ",
