                "name": "Justin Ma",
                "href": "/profile/Justin-Ma"
            },
            "answer_text": "Yes.  In my opinion, not often enough. This is noticeable when science starts spilling over into discussions involving policy, politics, religion, and philosophy. To be clear, by \"question,\" I mean asking what science is, where it starts and where it ends. The evolution-creation debates are by far the most obvious example.  In my (probably naive) view, the entire thing can be ended with some philosophical discussion, rather than the usual mess those arguments devolve into. A lot of the debate is basically about how life came about in the past.  By virtue of it being historical, it's never going to be fully testable, at least not without some assumptions.  The \"assumptions\" held by an evolutionary biologist studying it scientifically vs. the assumptions held a creationists are completely different.  Neither side is going to win over the other in those separate frameworks.  In my view, you miss this separation if you don't question what you're really asking and assuming as a scientist.  I see it missed by scientists all the time. ",
