            "author_info": {
                "name": "Marcus Geduld",
                "href": "/profile/Marcus-Geduld"
            },
            "answer_text": "Do scientists question the Scientific Method? Do they question whether it's a good way to do what it's meant to do, which is build predictive models? I doubt it, because it's proven time and again that it's the best method we have for building predictive models. If it wasn't, there's no way we'd have rovers on Mars or flu vaccines.  Do scientists question whether or not there are better ways to build predictive models? Some probably do, and it's a good question. But we have no answer to it. Our only choice right now is to use the best tool we have, and luckily for us it's worked in many situations.  There's an odd (and false) idea on Quora (and in popular culture) that most scientists are philosophers, studying science itself. Most aren't. They're too busy to think about that stuff. They've got a lab full of 1,000 samples in petri dishes, and they're making notes on each one, seeing if any of the samples turn green instead of blue. ",
