                "href": "/profile/Mike-Louis-Griebel"
            },
            "answer_text": "Yes, scientists (in natural sciences) always question all kinds of science. That's what it means to be a scientist, and that's what it means for a field to be a science. When a theory is questioned and tortured and tested, but is still standing, then there is reason to believe in it. But we must keep questioning them anyway. \"Or do you HAVE to start from that framework to stay in the scientific community?\" Look, anyone who seriously rocks the foundation of any science, establishing a new foundation, is hailed as a saviour, used as an inspiring example, and is more welcome than anyone else in the scientific community. But when you question the established theories, then you have to have some well-prepared arguments ready, or you won't have a chance. Only fair, I think. ",
